+.\"  -*- nroff -*-
+.\"
+.\" joymap.dat.5
+.\"
+.\" Man page created directly from author infos by
+.\" Cesare Falco <cesare.falco@gmail.com>, May 2007
+.TH JOYMAP.DAT 5 2007-05-26 0.115u2 "sdlmame"
+.\"
+.\" NAME chapter
+.SH NAME
+joymap.dat \- SDLMAME joystick mapping file
+.\"
+.\" DESCRIPTION chapter
+.SH DESCRIPTION
+With hot\-pluggable devices like USB joystick is almost unpredictable which one
+will be enumerated first by SDLMAME. This can easily lead to unwanted joystick
+switchings.
+
+With the joymap file, one can put each joystick into a logical slot,
+i.e. map it to a logical number SDLMAME will use.
+.\"
+.\" FILE FORMAT chapter
+.SH "FILE FORMAT"
+Each line of the file could be
+.TP
+.B \fBa comment\fR, starting with # \fI(hash sign)\fR, which will be ignored.
+.TP
+.B \fBa pair of values\fR, representing the SDLMAME logical_number and
+the joystick name. The name of each connected joystick can be determined with
+the \fBjstest\fR joystick test program.
+.\"
+.\" EXAMPLE chapter
+.SH "EXAMPLE"
+.br
+# Joystick mapping file
+.br
+# =====================
+.br
+#
+.br
+# Contains mapping between name and logical (i.e. mame) joystick index
+.br
+#
+.br
+# Index   Name
+.br
+# \-\-\-\-\-   \-\-\-\-
+.br
+    1     MOSIC USB 2A4K GamePad
+.br
+    0     Logitech Logitech Attack 3
+
+This file will map joystick "MOSIC USB 2A4K GamePad" to SDLMAME id 1 and
+"Logitech Logitech Attack 3" to SDLMAME id 0.
+.\"
+.\" HINTS chapter
+.SH "HINTS"
+If a joystick is not found and you have mapped SDLMAME codes in the ui
+to it, SDLMAME will just display "n/a". Connect the joystick, restart
+SDLMAME and the mappings will be there again.
+
+Joysticks which are not mapped will be put into free slots.
+.br
+\fBEXAMPLE\fR: You have mapped a joystick to slot 1. Connect a second
+joystick and it will be mapped to slot 0. A third would be mapped
+to slot 2.
+
+If you don't know the name of your joystick, first look at device names
+with \fBls \-l /dev/input/js*\fR and do \fBjstest /dev/input/js...\fR for
+each of them. The joystick name is the text enclosed in round brackets.
+.br
+\fBEXAMPLE\fR: if you find you have two joysticks connected, /dev/input/js0
+and /dev/input/js1, you have to run jstest /dev/input/js0 and then
+jstest /dev/input/js1.
+.\"
+.\" SEE ALSO chapter
+.SH "SEE ALSO"
+.BR jstest(1),
+.BR sdlmame(6).
